      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "Afterlives and Arguments",
        body: `<p>Chiaroscuro did not die with the Baroque. It migrated. The technique remains the foundational grammar of black-and-white photography, of film noir cinematography, of comic book ink work, and of contemporary digital lighting in animation and game design. When Gordon Willis lit <em>The Godfather</em> in 1972 with overhead sources that placed Marlon Brando's eyes in deep shadow, he was knowingly invoking Caravaggio. When Roger Deakins lit the interrogation scenes in <em>Blade Runner 2049</em>, he was working within a tradition that runs unbroken from the Contarelli Chapel.</p><p>Modern art-historical scholarship has reframed several of the older accounts. The seminal twentieth-century study, Walter Friedlaender's <em>Caravaggio Studies</em> (1955), established the painter's centrality but treated tenebrism as essentially a personal stylistic invention. More recent work — including Helen Langdon's <em>Caravaggio: A Life</em> (1998), Sebastian Schütze's catalogue raisonné for Taschen (2009, expanded 2017), and the technical studies coming out of the Getty Conservation Institute and the National Gallery of London — has emphasized how much Caravaggio drew on, and competed with, the lighting experiments of Lombard painters like Savoldo and Lotto, and how much the technique depended on workshop economies, patron expectations, and the cramped, low-lit chapels for which his pictures were designed. A Caravaggio altarpiece on a museum wall, lit from above by even gallery lighting, is in a meaningful sense being misread.</p><p>The attribution problem remains acute. The Caravaggesque manner spread so widely so quickly — through Bartolomeo Manfredi, Orazio Gentileschi, Valentin de Boulogne, Gerrit van Honthorst, and dozens of others — that distinguishing autograph Caravaggios from skilled follower work is genuinely difficult. The 2016 discovery of a painting in a Toulouse attic, identified by some scholars as Caravaggio's lost second <em>Judith and Holofernes</em> and sold privately in 2019 for an undisclosed sum, prompted a lively and unresolved scholarly dispute that played out in <em>The Art Newspaper</em> and the pages of academic journals. The pattern recurs: every decade brings new candidate Caravaggios, and the field divides.</p><p>The deepest current debate is conceptual. Recent work by scholars including Lorenzo Pericolo, in <em>Caravaggio and Pictorial Narrative</em> (2011), and Itay Sapir has argued that tenebrism is not merely a lighting choice but a thesis about the conditions of vision itself — a claim that human perception is fragmentary, partial, and always already darkened. Read this way, Caravaggio is not the founder of theatrical religious painting but the first European modernist: a painter who took the limits of seeing as his real subject. In that reading, every shadow he left on a canvas is an argument that there is more we are not being shown.</p>`
      }
