    levels: [
      {
        depth: 1,
        title: "A School That Outran Its Country",
        body: `<p>In 1919, in the small German city of Weimar, an architect named Walter Gropius opened an art school with an unusual idea: there should be no difference between art and craft. A painter and a carpenter, a weaver and a sculptor, should all train side by side. The new school called itself the Staatliches Bauhaus — literally, the "State Building House."</p><p>It lasted exactly fourteen years, moved cities twice, was harassed by city councils and police, and was finally shut down by the Gestapo in 1933. From beginning to end it never had more than a few hundred students. By any sensible measure it was a small, embattled experiment in a turbulent corner of a defeated country.</p><p>And yet. Almost every white wall you have ever stood next to, every sans-serif corporate logo, every black tubular-steel chair, every grid-based magazine layout, every modern apartment building with horizontal ribbon windows, every architecture school in the world, owes something — sometimes everything — to those fourteen years. The Bauhaus did not survive its century. It became its century.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "The Bauhaus did not survive its century. It became its century."
      },
      {
        depth: 2,
        title: "Art and Craft Reunited",
        body: `<p>The founding document, Gropius's manifesto of April 1919, opened with a sentence that still startles: <em>"The ultimate aim of all creative activity is the building."</em> The German word he chose, <em>Bau</em>, meant both "building" and "construction" — a total, cathedral-like project. The accompanying woodcut by Lyonel Feininger showed a Gothic cathedral with three stars over its towers: painting, sculpture, and architecture, reunited.</p><p>The premise was a deliberate inversion of the nineteenth-century art academy. In the academy, fine arts (painting, sculpture) stood above the applied arts (weaving, ceramics, furniture, typography), which were taught, when they were taught at all, in separate trade schools to a different class of student. Gropius proposed to dissolve that hierarchy entirely. Every Bauhaus student, regardless of intended specialism, would first complete a six-month <em>Vorkurs</em>, a preliminary course in material, color, and form, taught initially by the visionary Johannes Itten and later by László Moholy-Nagy and Josef Albers. After the <em>Vorkurs</em>, the student entered a workshop — weaving, metalwork, cabinetry, ceramics, mural painting, theater — under the joint instruction of two masters: a <em>Werkmeister</em> who knew the craft and a <em>Formmeister</em> who knew the art.</p><p>The roster of <em>Formmeister</em> was, in retrospect, almost absurd. Paul Klee taught form theory. Wassily Kandinsky taught color theory. Lyonel Feininger ran the printmaking workshop. Oskar Schlemmer ran the theater workshop. Marcel Breuer ran cabinetry. Anni Albers ran weaving. Marianne Brandt ran metalwork. Mies van der Rohe — the last director, from 1930 to 1933 — would, two decades later, design the Seagram Building.</p><p>For a school of perhaps 150 students at any given time, this was a faculty of unreasonable quality, gathered in one place in the brief window when Weimar Germany could afford to host them.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "The ultimate aim of all creative activity is the building."
      },
      {
        depth: 3,
        title: "Three Cities, Three Phases",
        body: `<p>The school's fourteen years divide neatly into three phases, each defined by a city, a director, and a sensibility.</p><p>The Weimar period, 1919 to 1925, was the romantic phase. Gropius's earliest collaborator, the Swiss painter Johannes Itten, was a charismatic mystic — a vegetarian, a Mazdaznan acolyte, a man who began his classes with breathing exercises and chanted color contemplations. The early Bauhaus had a strongly expressionist temperament, deeply suspicious of industrial production, dedicated to the recovery of pre-modern craft sensibility. Itten was eventually pushed out in 1923, and the school began its turn toward the machine.</p><p>The Dessau period, 1925 to 1932, was the classical phase, and the one most people picture when they think of the Bauhaus. After Weimar's right-wing city council withdrew funding, the social democratic city of Dessau invited the school north and built it a new campus. Gropius designed the building himself: a low-slung, white-walled, flat-roofed complex with glass curtain walls on its workshop wing and clean rectilinear dorms, completed in 1926 and now a UNESCO World Heritage Site. It was the first building most people had ever seen that looked like the twentieth century. The Dessau period produced the canonical Bauhaus objects: Marcel Breuer's tubular-steel Wassily Chair (1925), Wilhelm Wagenfeld's glass-and-metal table lamp (1924), Marianne Brandt's spherical brass ashtray and tea infusers, Herbert Bayer's universal lowercase typography, the geometric Bauhaus chess set by Josef Hartwig (1924).</p><p>The Berlin period, 1932 to 1933, was the brief, defensive coda. After the National Socialists took Dessau's city council and again withdrew funding, Mies van der Rohe relocated the school to a disused telephone factory in the Steglitz district of Berlin. It functioned for less than a year. On April 11, 1933, the Gestapo raided the building and sealed it. Mies dissolved the school on July 20, 1933.</p><p>The diaspora that followed scattered the faculty across the world. Gropius and Breuer to Harvard. Mies to the Illinois Institute of Technology in Chicago, where his architecture would shape postwar America. Moholy-Nagy to the New Bauhaus in Chicago, the ancestor of today's Institute of Design at IIT. Anni and Josef Albers to Black Mountain College in North Carolina and later Yale. The school was killed; its ideas were exported.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 4,
        title: "A Philosophy of Form",
        body: `<p>Behind the school's distinctive look lay a coherent, if internally contested, philosophy of form. Three propositions structured the Bauhaus's intellectual life.</p><p>First, the unity of form and function. The phrase <em>form follows function</em>, coined by the American architect Louis Sullivan in 1896, was not Bauhaus doctrine but it expressed an ambient conviction: that the proper shape of any object can be derived rationally from its purpose, its materials, and its method of production. A teapot is not a sculpture to be decorated; it is a vessel that pours, retains heat, and is filled. The proper teapot is the one in which these requirements are most lucidly resolved. Marianne Brandt's silver teapot of 1924 — a perfect hemisphere with a tiny offset spout and an ebony handle — is the canonical statement of the principle.</p><p>Second, the rational analysis of perception. Kandinsky's <em>Punkt und Linie zu Fläche</em> ("Point and Line to Plane"), published in 1926 as part of the Bauhausbücher series, attempted to derive the entire vocabulary of pictorial form from primitive elements. Klee's <em>Pädagogisches Skizzenbuch</em> ("Pedagogical Sketchbook"), 1925, did something similar for drawing. Itten and later Albers ran extensive studies of color interaction, demonstrating that any given color shifts perceptually depending on its neighbors — a finding Josef Albers would spend his entire late career developing in his <em>Homage to the Square</em> series and his book <em>Interaction of Color</em> (1963).</p><p>Third, the embrace of industrial production. Where William Morris and the British Arts and Crafts movement of the nineteenth century had treated the machine as the enemy of honest making, the mature Bauhaus reversed the polarity. The proper artist did not flee the factory; the proper artist designed for it. Mass production was not a debasement of craft but its democratic fulfillment. A well-designed lamp produced in twenty thousand copies served twenty thousand homes; a hand-thrown lamp served one. The political logic was implicit but real: good design was egalitarian.</p><p>These propositions, in practice, were never wholly consistent. The handmade Bauhaus weaving workshop — the school's most commercially successful department, dominated almost entirely by women including Anni Albers, Gunta Stölzl, and Otti Berger — produced textiles in small editions on hand looms even as the rhetoric celebrated industry. The metalwork shop's most famous products were prototypes that never saw mass production. The contradiction was generative.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 5,
        title: "Objects and Their Specifications",
        body: `<p>The mature Bauhaus product is best understood through specific objects. Consider four canonical examples.</p><p>Marcel Breuer's <em>Wassily Chair</em> (B3), designed in Dessau in 1925, is generally regarded as the first piece of furniture to use tubular steel as a structural material. Breuer, twenty-three years old at the time, was reportedly inspired by the handlebars of his Adler bicycle. The chair frame is a single continuous bent steel tube, chrome-plated, with leather or canvas slings forming the seat, back, and armrests. The design dematerialized the traditional armchair: where a Biedermeier armchair was a heavy upholstered mass, the B3 was a wireframe diagram of a chair, weighing approximately 8 kilograms. It went into production with the Standard-Möbel firm in 1926 and is still manufactured today by Knoll under the name Wassily, after Kandinsky, who was given an early example.</p><p>Wilhelm Wagenfeld's table lamp, designed in 1924 in the metalwork workshop, distilled the form of the desk lamp to four primitive geometric elements: a circular base, a vertical cylindrical stem, a spherical opal-glass shade, and a small chrome on-off switch. The original (designated MT8 in the workshop catalogue) measured approximately 36 centimeters tall with a 16-centimeter diameter shade, base of nickeled metal, shade of mouth-blown matt-white opal glass. The lamp is in continuous production by Tecnolumen since 1980 and sits in the design collections of the Museum of Modern Art in New York, the Victoria and Albert Museum in London, and the Bauhaus-Archiv Berlin.</p><p>Herbert Bayer's <em>universal typeface</em>, drawn in Dessau in 1925, attempted to eliminate capital letters entirely. Bayer's argument, set out in his essay "on typography" (1927, lowercase throughout), was that the German practice of capitalizing all nouns was a historical accident with no phonetic justification, and that a single lowercase alphabet was both more rational and more efficient. The Bauhaus adopted the convention for all its publications from 1925 onward, and Bayer's geometric, sans-serif <em>Universal</em> alphabet — drawn entirely from compass-and-ruler primitives — became the school's house style. It is the direct ancestor of every geometric sans-serif of the twentieth century, including Futura (1927), Helvetica (1957), Avenir (1988), and the typeface in which much of the modern web is set.</p><p>The Bauhaus building itself in Dessau, completed in 1926 under Gropius's direction, totals approximately 28,000 cubic meters across three connected wings: the workshop block (with its famous fully glazed curtain wall, an early use of a non-load-bearing glass facade), the technical school block, and the dormitory and atelier block (the <em>Prellerhaus</em>) with 28 small studio apartments for senior students. Materials: reinforced concrete frame, brick infill, steel-framed glazing, white-pebbledash render. Reconstruction after war damage was carried out from the 1970s; the building was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage list in 1996 and now houses the Bauhaus Dessau Foundation.</p><p>The internal economic logic of the workshops varied:</p><pre>
Workshop          Director (Formmeister)    Sales model
weaving           Anni Albers, Gunta Stölzl handmade editions
metal             Moholy-Nagy / Marianne    industrial license
                  Brandt
cabinetry         Marcel Breuer             licensed prototypes
typography        Herbert Bayer             internal use,
                                            commercial commissions
ceramics          Gerhard Marcks            small editions,
                                            kiln-fired Dornburg
theater           Oskar Schlemmer           performance only
mural painting    Wassily Kandinsky         architectural commissions
</pre><p>The metal workshop's licensing agreements — particularly Brandt's Kandem lamps, mass-produced by Körting &amp; Mathiesen from 1928 — were among the most commercially successful Bauhaus products and helped fund the school during its precarious final years.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "Inheritance and Reappraisal",
        body: `<p>The Bauhaus's afterlife dwarfs its institutional existence. The diaspora of 1933 transplanted the pedagogy directly into American architectural and design education. Gropius's tenure at the Harvard Graduate School of Design from 1937 reshaped Anglo-American architectural training; Mies's at the Illinois Institute of Technology in Chicago produced the postwar International Style; Moholy-Nagy's New Bauhaus in Chicago, founded 1937 and now the Institute of Design at IIT, exported the <em>Vorkurs</em> model to American design schools; Josef and Anni Albers at Black Mountain College and later Yale shaped two generations of American painters and weavers.</p><p>Postwar German design — Dieter Rams at Braun, the Hochschule für Gestaltung in Ulm under Max Bill (himself a Bauhaus graduate) from 1953 to 1968, the entire visual identity of the Federal Republic — was self-consciously Bauhaus-derived. Apple's late-twentieth and early-twenty-first century product design, particularly under Jonathan Ive, drew explicitly on Rams's reductivist principles, which in turn drew on Brandt and Wagenfeld. The throughline runs cleanly from Brandt's 1924 silver teapot to the first-generation Apple iPod (2001).</p><p>Modern scholarship has spent the past several decades complicating the hagiography. Major recent contributions include Magdalena Droste's <em>Bauhaus</em> (Taschen, revised 2019, the standard reference work), Anja Baumhoff's <em>The Gendered World of the Bauhaus</em> (2001) and Patrick Rössler's research recovering the work of women who were systematically underweighted in the school's official history — Lucia Moholy, whose photographs of the Dessau building defined the school's image while her own attribution was suppressed for decades; Marianne Brandt, whose metalwork was for years attributed to her male <em>Werkmeister</em>; Anni Albers, whose textile work was long treated as derivative of her husband's. The 2019 centenary exhibitions at the Bauhaus-Archiv Berlin, Tate Modern, and MoMA all foregrounded these reappraisals.</p><p>Open debates persist. Was the Bauhaus a left-wing project, as Hannes Meyer (director 1928–1930, a committed Marxist) insisted, or a politically pragmatic one as Gropius preferred? How much of the school's ideology was specific to Weimar Germany's particular crisis of modernity, and how much is genuinely universal? The Israeli historian Sharon Rotbard, in <em>White City, Black City</em> (2015), has argued that the celebrated "white city" of Tel Aviv's modernist 1930s architecture — built largely by Bauhaus-trained refugees and inscribed by UNESCO in 2003 — was constructed in part by erasing the Palestinian city of Jaffa, raising hard questions about whose modernism the Bauhaus ultimately served.</p><p>The school itself lasted fourteen years. The century that followed, in design at least, has been a long footnote to its experiments. Whether that constitutes triumph or trap is, a hundred years on, an open and increasingly interesting question.</p>`
      }
    ]
